mercantilism) defended even a much more sophisticated and
interventionist role of the state in the economy-for example, the role
of identifying and developing strategic and targeted industries (i.e.
industries considered vital to long-term economic growth) through a
variety of means, including tax policy, subsidization, banking
regulation, labor control, and interest-rate management.
